04756nam a22007215i 9780813564159DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2015028626  a97808135641597 a10.36019/97808135641592doi  a(DE-B1597)530155  a(OCoLC)945447753  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN1995.7b.B43 2016 4aPN1995.7 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.4302/42231 aBeck, Jay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDesigning Sound :bAudiovisual Aesthetics in 1970s American Cinema /cJay Beck. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (274 p.) :b25 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTechniques of the Moving Image00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: The State of the Art -- tPART ONE. General Trends (1965–1971) -- t2. The British Invasion -- t3. TV and Documentary’s Influence on Sound Aesthetics -- t4. New Voices and Personal Sound Aesthetics, 1970–1971 -- tPART TWO. Director Case Studies (1968–1976) -- t5. Francis Ford Coppola’s American Zoetrope and Collective Filmmaking -- t6. Robert Altman’s Collaborative Sound Work -- t7. Martin Scorsese’s Dialectical Sound -- tPART THREE. The Dolby Stereo Era (1975–1980) -- t8. The Sound of Music -- t9. The Sound of Spectacle: Dolby Stereo and the New Classicism -- t10. The Sound of Storytelling: Dolby Stereo and the Art of Sound Design -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe late 1960s and 1970s are widely recognized as a golden age for American film, as directors like Francis Ford Coppola, George Lucas, and Martin Scorsese expanded the Hollywood model with aesthetically innovative works. As this groundbreaking new study reveals, those filmmakers were blessed with more than just visionary eyes; Designing Sound focuses on how those filmmakers also had keen ears that enabled them to perceive new possibilities for cinematic sound design. Offering detailed case studies of key films and filmmakers, Jay Beck explores how sound design was central to the era’s experimentation with new modes of cinematic storytelling. He demonstrates how sound was key to many directors’ signature aesthetics, from the overlapping dialogue that contributes to Robert Altman’s naturalism to the wordless interludes at the heart of Terrence Malick’s lyricism. Yet the book also examines sound design as a collaborative process, one where certain key directors ceded authority to sound technicians who offered significant creative input. Designing Sound provides readers with a fresh take on a much-studied era in American film, giving a new appreciation of how artistry emerged from a period of rapid industrial and technological change. Filled with rich behind-the-scenes details, the book vividly conveys how sound practices developed by 1970s filmmakers changed the course of American cinema.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMotion picturesxProduction and directionzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSound motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066614440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356415940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813564159423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813564159.jpg  a978-3-11-066614-4  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13EN